[3]
Date: 25 Jun 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/N24201125.htm>


US finds 2nd mad cow, industry defends safeguards
-----------------------------------------------
[There is a lot of repetition in all of these articles, but the
following points are pertinent. - Mod.MHJ]

Ron DeHaven, head of the USDA's Animal and Plant Health Inspection,
said the infected animal was slaughtered at a pet food plant [a
renderer]. Neither official [DeHaven and U.S. Agriculture Secretary
Mike Johanns] would identify the state where the cow came from.
Published reports have said it was sent to slaughter last November
2004 in Texas, the nation's biggest cattle state.

Officials said the infected animal was born before a 1997 ban on
recycling cattle remains into cattle rations. There was no evidence
the infected animal was imported, said the USDA, which was doing DNA
testing to confirm its herd of origin.

USDA officials said the new BSE case was a different strain from the
1st U.S. case and the outbreak that occurred in Britain in the 1980s.
Some experts had speculated the conflicting test results were due to
an unusual type of BSE. [It has been likened to a European strain of
BSE. - Mod.MHJ]

[Byline: Charles Abbott and Sophie Walker]

