Date: 24 Jun 2005
From: Mary Marshall <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/N24700329.htm>


Canada says no surprise U.S. finds mad cow case
-----------------------------------------------
Canadian Prime Minister Paul Martin said on Friday [24 Jun 2005] that
it was no surprise the United States had discovered a case of mad cow
disease, or BSE, and urged Washington to reopen the border to
Canadian cattle shipments. "That border should have been opened a
long time ago, based on very sound science," Martin told reporters in
High River, Alberta. "The Canadian means of determining BSE (bovine
spongiform encephalopathy), of controlling BSE, is among the world's
best. That there is a case in the U.S. is not a surprise.
And...hopefully -- judges and court decisions and injunctions to the
contrary -- the view of (the U.S. Department of Agriculture) and the
U.S. administration should prevail. That border should be open and it
should be open now."

Canada has reported 3 cases of mad cow disease since May 2003.
Another cow with the disease was found in Washington state in
December 2003 and was born in Canada. The United States closed its
border to Canadian cattle when the 1st case was discovered in Alberta
2 years ago. The U.S. agriculture department has tried to open up the
border to young cattle from Canada, but has been stopped by an
injunction granted by a federal judge in Montana.

--
